---
import Layout from "../../../layouts/Layout.astro";
import SaltCapCalculator from "../../../components/SaltCapCalculator.astro";
---

<Layout
  title="SALT Cap Deduction Calculator | 2026 $40,400 Limit Explained (Australia)"
  description="See exactly how much of your state and local tax deduction you can claim under the new $40,400 SALT cap, including the high-income phase-down."
>
  <script type="application/ld+json" slot="head">
  {
    "@context": "https://schema.org",
    "@graph": [
      {
        "@type": "FinanceApplication",
        "name": "SALT Cap Deduction Calculator",
        "applicationCategory": "FinanceApplication",
        "operatingSystem": "Web",
        "provider": {
          "@id": "https://taxdebtwealthsuite.com/#organization"
        },
        "offers": {
          "@type": "Offer",
          "price": "0",
          "priceCurrency": "USD"
        },
        "description": "See exactly how much of your state and local tax deduction you can claim under the new $40,400 SALT cap, including the high-income phase-down."
      },
      {
        "@type": "FAQPage",
        "mainEntity": [
          {
            "@type": "Question",
            "name": "Why did the SALT cap increase in 2026?",
            "acceptedAnswer": {
              "@type": "Answer",
              "text": "The One Big Beautiful Bill Act (OBBBA), signed in July 2025, raised the SALT deduction cap from $10,000 to $40,000 for 2025, indexed to roughly $40,400 for 2026, through 2029. Unless extended, the cap reverts to $10,000 in 2030."
            }
          },
          {
            "@type": "Question",
            "name": "What happens to the SALT cap if I earn over $505,000?",
            "acceptedAnswer": {
              "@type": "Answer",
              "text": "The cap phases down $1 for every $1 of Modified AGI above roughly $505,000 ($252,500 for married filing separately), but it never falls below the pre-OBBBA floor of $10,000 ($5,000 for married filing separately)."
            }
          },
          {
            "@type": "Question",
            "name": "Is SALT deductible for the Alternative Minimum Tax?",
            "acceptedAnswer": {
              "@type": "Answer",
              "text": "No. State and local taxes are added back when calculating Alternative Minimum Taxable Income, so a large SALT deduction under the regular rules can still increase your AMT exposure."
            }
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "@type": "BreadcrumbList",
        "itemListElement": [
          {
            "@type": "ListItem",
            "position": 1,
            "name": "Home",
            "item": "https://taxdebtwealthsuite.com/"
          },
          {
            "@type": "ListItem",
            "position": 2,
            "name": "SALT Cap Deduction Calculator",
            "item": "https://taxdebtwealthsuite.com/salt-cap-deduction-calculator/"
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  }
  </script>

  <main class="flex-grow max-w-7xl w-full mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8 py-6 sm:py-10">

    <!-- Title Section -->
    <div class="mb-8 text-center sm:text-left">
      <h1 class="text-3xl font-extrabold text-white tracking-tight font-sans">
        SALT Cap Deduction Calculator (2026)
       (Australia)</h1>
      <div class="mt-4 flex flex-wrap items-center gap-3 text-xs font-medium text-slate-500 bg-slate-900/50 inline-flex px-3 py-1.5 rounded-lg border border-slate-800">
        <div class="flex items-center gap-1.5">
          <svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" class="h-4 w-4 text-[#00F5D4]" fill="none" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" d="M9 12l2 2 4-4m5.618-4.016A11.955 11.955 0 0112 2.944a11.955 11.955 0 01-8.618 3.04A12.02 12.02 0 003 9c0 5.591 3.824 10.29 9 11.622 5.176-1.332 9-6.03 9-11.622 0-1.042-.133-2.052-.382-3.016z"/></svg>
          <span>Reviewed by <a href="/editorial-policy/" class="text-slate-400 hover:text-[#00F5D4] transition-colors underline decoration-slate-700 underline-offset-2">Editorial Staff</a></span>
        </div>
        <span class="hidden sm:inline text-slate-700">&bull;</span>
        <time datetime="2026-07-21" class="text-slate-400">Updated: July 2026</time>
      </div>
      <p class="text-sm text-slate-400 mt-2 max-w-2xl leading-relaxed">
        See your exact allowed state and local tax deduction under the new $40,400 SALT cap, including the high-income phase-down, and compare itemizing vs. the standard deduction.
      </p>
      <div class="mt-4 text-xs text-slate-400">
        Switch to another country variant: 
        <a href="/salt-cap-deduction-calculator/" class="text-[#00F5D4] hover:underline">United States (Default)</a> | 
        <a href="/salt-cap-deduction-calculator/uk/" class="text-[#00F5D4] hover:underline">United Kingdom</a> | 
        <a href="/salt-cap-deduction-calculator/canada/" class="text-[#00F5D4] hover:underline">Canada</a> | 
        <span class="text-slate-300 font-semibold">Australia</span>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- Calculator Component Island -->
    <SaltCapCalculator />

    <!-- Explainer Content -->
    <div class="border-t border-slate-800/60 mt-12 bg-gradient-to-b from-slate-950 to-slate-950/95">
      <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto py-16">
        <section>
          <div class="mb-6">
            <span class="inline-flex items-center px-3 py-1 rounded-full text-xs font-bold uppercase tracking-widest bg-indigo-500/10 text-indigo-400 border border-indigo-500/20 mb-4">Financial Tool</span>
            <h2 class="text-2xl sm:text-3xl font-extrabold text-white tracking-tight leading-snug">
              Know Exactly What Your SALT Deduction Is Worth
            </h2>
          </div>

          <div class="space-y-8 text-sm text-slate-400 leading-relaxed">
            <article>
              <h3 class="text-xl font-bold text-slate-100 mb-3">Introduction</h3>
              <p>The One Big Beautiful Bill Act raised the SALT (state and local tax) deduction cap from $10,000 to $40,000 starting in 2025, indexed to roughly $40,400 for 2026, through 2029. But the increase phases down for taxpayers with Modified AGI above roughly $505,000 — so the actual benefit depends heavily on where your income falls. This calculator shows your real allowed deduction, not just the headline cap.</p>
            </article>

            <article>
              <h3 class="text-xl font-bold text-slate-100 mb-3">Key Benefits</h3>
              <ul class="list-disc pl-5 space-y-2">
                <li>See your exact allowed SALT deduction after any high-income phase-down.</li>
                <li>Instantly compare itemizing vs. the standard deduction.</li>
                <li>See exactly how much SALT deduction you're losing to the cap, if any.</li>
                <li>Understand your AMT exposure risk from a large SALT deduction.</li>
              </ul>
            </article>
          </div>

          <!-- FAQ Accordion -->
          <div class="mt-12 border-t border-slate-800/80 pt-10">
            <span class="inline-flex items-center px-3 py-1 rounded-full text-xs font-bold uppercase tracking-widest bg-amber-500/10 text-amber-400 border border-amber-500/20 mb-4">FAQ</span>
            <h3 class="text-2xl font-bold text-white mb-6">Frequently Asked Questions</h3>

            <div class="space-y-4">
              <div class="border border-slate-800 rounded-lg overflow-hidden bg-slate-900/50">
                <button class="w-full flex items-center justify-between px-6 py-5 text-left group cursor-pointer" onclick="this.nextElementSibling.classList.toggle('hidden'); this.querySelector('svg').classList.toggle('rotate-180');">
                  <span class="font-semibold text-white">Why did the SALT cap increase in 2026?</span>
                  <svg class="h-5 w-5 text-slate-500 transition-transform duration-200" fill="none" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7"/></svg>
                </button>
                <div class="hidden px-6 pb-6 text-sm text-slate-400">
                  The One Big Beautiful Bill Act (OBBBA), signed in July 2025, raised the SALT deduction cap from $10,000 to $40,000 for 2025, indexed to roughly $40,400 for 2026, through 2029. Unless extended, the cap reverts to $10,000 in 2030.
                </div>
              </div>
              <div class="border border-slate-800 rounded-lg overflow-hidden bg-slate-900/50">
                <button class="w-full flex items-center justify-between px-6 py-5 text-left group cursor-pointer" onclick="this.nextElementSibling.classList.toggle('hidden'); this.querySelector('svg').classList.toggle('rotate-180');">
                  <span class="font-semibold text-white">What happens to the SALT cap if I earn over $505,000?</span>
                  <svg class="h-5 w-5 text-slate-500 transition-transform duration-200" fill="none" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7"/></svg>
                </button>
                <div class="hidden px-6 pb-6 text-sm text-slate-400">
                  The cap phases down $1 for every $1 of Modified AGI above roughly $505,000 ($252,500 for married filing separately), but it never falls below the pre-OBBBA floor of $10,000 ($5,000 for married filing separately).
                </div>
              </div>
              <div class="border border-slate-800 rounded-lg overflow-hidden bg-slate-900/50">
                <button class="w-full flex items-center justify-between px-6 py-5 text-left group cursor-pointer" onclick="this.nextElementSibling.classList.toggle('hidden'); this.querySelector('svg').classList.toggle('rotate-180');">
                  <span class="font-semibold text-white">Is SALT deductible for the Alternative Minimum Tax?</span>
                  <svg class="h-5 w-5 text-slate-500 transition-transform duration-200" fill="none" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7"/></svg>
                </button>
                <div class="hidden px-6 pb-6 text-sm text-slate-400">
                  No. State and local taxes are added back when calculating Alternative Minimum Taxable Income, so a large SALT deduction under the regular rules can still increase your AMT exposure.
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <!-- Internal Links -->
          <div class="mt-12 border-t border-slate-800/80 pt-10">
            <h3 class="text-xl font-bold text-white mb-4">Related Calculators &amp; Resources</h3>
            <div class="flex flex-col space-y-2">
              <a href="/qbi-deduction-calculator/" class="text-[#00F5D4] hover:underline">QBI Deduction Calculator</a>
              <a href="/s-corp-tax-calculator/" class="text-[#00F5D4] hover:underline">S-Corp Tax Calculator</a>
              <a href="/buy-borrow-die-calculator/" class="text-[#00F5D4] hover:underline">Buy, Borrow, Die Calculator</a>
            </div>
          </div>

          <!-- Methodology & Sources -->
          <div class="mt-12 border-t border-slate-800/80 pt-10">
            <span class="inline-flex items-center px-3 py-1 rounded-full text-xs font-bold uppercase tracking-widest bg-emerald-500/10 text-emerald-400 border border-emerald-500/20 mb-4">Methodology</span>
            <h3 class="text-2xl font-bold text-white mb-4">How This is Calculated</h3>
            <div class="text-sm text-slate-400 space-y-3 leading-relaxed">
              <p>This calculator adds your state/local income (or sales) tax and property tax to get your raw SALT total, then applies the 2026 cap ($40,400 for Single/MFJ/HOH, $20,200 for MFS). If your Modified AGI exceeds the phase-out threshold (roughly $505,000, or $252,500 for MFS), the cap is reduced dollar-for-dollar by the excess, down to a floor of $10,000 ($5,000 for MFS). Your allowed SALT deduction is then added to mortgage interest, charitable contributions, and other itemizable deductions, and compared against the standard deduction for your filing status.</p>
              <p>This is a simplified estimate — it doesn't model Pass-Through Entity (PTE) tax elections, which many states allow as a workaround for business owners, or interactions with other AMT preference items. Consult a tax professional for your specific situation.</p>
              <p><strong>Official Source:</strong> <a href="https://www.irs.gov/newsroom" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="text-emerald-400 hover:underline">IRS.gov — Newsroom &amp; Tax Law Updates</a></p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </section>
      </div>
    </div>
  </main>
</Layout>
